                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d302">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.4184/30: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Engert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Addis Ababa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-05-27T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 27, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>374. Legation’s 334, May 12,<note n="32" xml:id="d302fn32">Not printed.</note>
                    and Department’s 227, May 14. I learn that British and French Governments have
                    both declined to comply with Italian request that their respective legation
                    guards be withdrawn as they do not yet consider local situation sufficiently
                    settled to warrant it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
